07184nam a22011895i 9783110198508DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831101985087 a10.1515/97831101985082doi  a(DE-B1597)34874  a(OCoLC)979583673  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP120.V37bS789 2007eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a41022200aStyle and Social Identities :bAlternative Approaches to Linguistic Heterogeneity /ced. by Peter Auer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (513 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage, Power and Social Process [LPSP] ,x1861-4175 ;v180 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume presents an interactional perspective on linguistic variability that takes into account the construction of social identities through the formation of social communicative styles. It shows that style is a useful category in bridging the gap between single parameter variation and social identity. Social positioning, i.e., finding one's place in society, is one of its motivating forces. Various aspects of the expression of stylistic features are focused on, from language choice and linguistic variation in a narrow sense to practices of social categorization, pragmatics patterns, preferences for specific communicative genres, rhetorical practices including prosodic features, and aesthetic choices and preferences for specific forms of taste (looks, clothes, music, etc.). These various features of expression are connected to multimodal stylistic indices through talk; thus, styles emerge from discourse. Styles are adapted to changing contexts, and develop in the course of social processes. The analytical perspective chosen proposes an alternative to current approaches to variability under the influence of the so-called variationist paradigm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGroup identity. 0aIdentity (Psychology). 0aLanguage and languagesxStyle. 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aSoziale Indentität. 4aSprachsoziologie. 4adiscourse analysis. 4asocial identity. 4asociolinguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSociolinguistics.  adiscourse analysis.  asocial identity.1 aAndroutsopoulos, Jannis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnhold, Jacinta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuer, Peter , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAuer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBierbach, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirken-Silverman, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBueno-Aniola, Cintia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook-Gumperz, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoupland, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDailey-O’Cain, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeppermann, Arnulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFina, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgakopoulou, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGumperz, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGünthner, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeim, Inken, econtributor.4ctb4http